@SomXerxesIII On Twitter 
Current Location : Miami, FL - Earth

@Zeyyrixx many people care about climate change and are economically and societally disadvantaged making it more difficult to do something about it. When it's between survival and basic needs versus protecting the planet, people will try to find ways to survive. It's hard to think about reducing, reusing, and recycling when you live in an apartment with no heat in the middle of winter.

People also were taught wrong. The hierarchy of what's important for someone to work on for climate change became recycle, reuse, reduce instead of reduce, reuse, and recycle. I see this happen because people just recycle anything they think can be recycled (which 30% if the time they're wrong) because they're helping. Chicago has warehouses full of cardboard because they do not have the capacity to process the amount they get. This phenomena is also part of society. You can't go up to someone who has been living the life of fast fashion for two decades and convince them to stop even if they have the financial means to. You have to speak their language in order to get them to understand. For some people, that's the news. Others, movies and entertainment is more effective. The bottom line is though, many are told and understand the threat and are also in poverty struggling to survive. 

In my humble opinion, the world should focus on improving public transportation and building cities in a way that supports public transit rather than places like the US where streets built for roads are everywhere. Not only does public transportation reduce climate change, affordable and accessible transportation is the number one factor in getting people out of poverty. If people have more money, they can focus on what they're buying more rather than finding the cheapest meal options.
